Q1. What is serialization in Java?
-->Serialization is the process of converting a Java object into a byte stream so that it can be:

    Stored in a file.
    Sent over a network.
    Saved in a database.
    Transferred between applications.
    
    Java performs serialization using the ObjectOutputStream class.
    
    The class whose objects are to be serialized must implement the Serializable interface.
    
    Example
    class Student implements Serializable {
        int id = 101;
        String name = "John";
    }
    ObjectOutputStream oos =
        new ObjectOutputStream(new FileOutputStream("student.dat"));
    
    oos.writeObject(student);
    Interview One-Liner
    
    Serialization is the process of converting a Java object into a byte stream so it can be stored, transferred, or transmitted. 
    It is performed using ObjectOutputStream, and the class must implement the Serializable interface.




Q2. How can you make a class serializable in Java?
-->To make a class serializable, simply implement the Serializable interface.

    Since Serializable is a marker interface, you don't need to implement any methods.
    
    Example
    import java.io.Serializable;
    
    class Student implements Serializable {
        int id;
        String name;
    }
    
    Now objects of the Student class can be serialized using ObjectOutputStream.
    
    Interview One-Liner
    
    A class can be made serializable by implementing the java.io.Serializable marker interface. Since it contains no methods, no implementation
    is required.




Q3. How can you prevent serialization in a subclass when the parent class implements the Serializable interface?
-->Normally, if a parent class implements Serializable, then all its subclasses are automatically serializable.

            There is no way to "unimplement" Serializable in the subclass.
            
            To prevent serialization of the subclass, you can override the serialization process and throw a NotSerializableException.
            
            Example
            import java.io.*;
            
            class Parent implements Serializable { }
            
            class Child extends Parent {
            
                private void writeObject(ObjectOutputStream out) throws IOException {
                    throw new NotSerializableException("Child cannot be serialized");
                }
            }
            Interview One-Liner
            
            A subclass of a serializable parent is automatically serializable. It cannot remove Serializable, but it can prevent serialization by overriding writeObject() and throwing NotSerializableException.







Q4. Can a serialized object be transferred over a network?
-->Yes.
    
    A serialized object is converted into a byte stream, which can be transmitted over a network using streams such as Socket, ObjectOutputStream,
    and ObjectInputStream.
    
    The sender serializes the object, and the receiver deserializes it back into the original object.
    
    Example
    
    Sender
    
    ObjectOutputStream oos =
        new ObjectOutputStream(socket.getOutputStream());
    
    oos.writeObject(student);
    
    Receiver
    
    ObjectInputStream ois =
        new ObjectInputStream(socket.getInputStream());
    
    Student s = (Student) ois.readObject();
    Interview One-Liner
    
    Yes. A serialized object can be transferred over a network because serialization converts the object into a byte stream,
    which can be sent through a socket and reconstructed on the receiving side using deserialization.




Q5. What is deserialization in Java?
-->Deserialization is the process of converting a byte stream back into a Java object.

    It is the reverse process of serialization.
    
    Java performs deserialization using the ObjectInputStream class.
    
    The class must implement the Serializable interface.
    
    Example
    import java.io.*;
    
    ObjectInputStream ois =
        new ObjectInputStream(new FileInputStream("student.dat"));
    
    Student s = (Student) ois.readObject();
    
    ois.close();
    Key Method
    readObject();
    
    This method reads the serialized object from the file and reconstructs the original object.
    
    Interview One-Liner
    
    Deserialization is the process of converting a byte stream back into a Java object. It is performed using ObjectInputStream and the readObject()
    method.




Q6. What is the purpose of the transient keyword in serialization?
-->The transient keyword is used to prevent a field from being serialized.
    
    When an object is serialized, all non-transient fields are saved. A transient field is skipped, and after deserialization, it gets its default value.
    
    Example
    import java.io.Serializable;
    
    class Student implements Serializable {
    
        int id = 101;
        String name = "Karthikeya";
    
        transient String password = "admin123";
    }
    
    If the Student object is serialized and then deserialized:
    
    id → 101 ✅
    name → "Karthikeya" ✅
    password → null ❌ (not serialized)
    Why use transient?
    
    To avoid serializing sensitive or unnecessary data, such as:
    
    Passwords
    OTPs
    Temporary data
    Cache values
    Interview One-Liner
    
    The transient keyword is used to exclude a field from serialization. After deserialization, the transient field is restored to its default
    value instead of its original value.



